os are expanded, the complete AST is lowered to HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation):\n\n- The entry point is `lower_to_hir()` in `compiler/rustc_ast_lowering/src/lib.rs` (line 485), registered as a query provider at `compiler/rustc_interface/src/passes.rs` line 888.\n\n- `LoweringContext` (line 91 in lib.rs) is the main structure managing the lowering process, maintaining:\n  - The `arena` for allocating HIR nodes\n  - `resolver`: Symbol resolution information\n  - `bodies`: Collected function bodies\n  - Various context state (loop scopes, async contexts, etc.)\n\n- Item lowering is handled in `compiler/rustc_ast_lowering/src/item.rs` where `lower_item()` (line 136) converts AST items to HIR items. Similar functions exist for expressions, patterns, types, etc. in their respective modules (expr.rs, pat.rs, path.rs, etc.).\n\n## Complete Flow Summary\n\nThe macro expansion to HIR lowering chain is:\n\n1. `macro_expand_crate` (in passes.rs) calls\n2. `MacroExpander::expand_crate()` which calls\n3. `fully_expand_fragment()` which:\n   - Calls `collect_invocations()` to find all macro invocations\n   - Calls `expand_invoc()` on each invocation, which dispatches to:\n     - For declarative macros: `TtParser::parse_tt()` + `transcribe()`\n     - For procedural macros: `BangProcMacro::expand()` / `AttrProcMacro::expand()`\n   - Calls `parse_ast_fragment()` to convert token streams to AST\n4. The fully expanded AST is then passed to\n5. `lower_to_hir()` which uses `LoweringContext` to convert AST to HIR\n\nThis pipeline maintains span information throughout to enable error reporting and source mapping, uses hygiene information to ensure macro-generated identifiers are properly scoped, and handles both eager (macro_rules with special evaluation semantics) and lazy (most macros) expansion modes."
